{"title_page": "Loraine Felix", "text_new": "{{Notability|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Loraine Felix.jpg|thumb|Loraine Felix]]\n\n'''Loraine Felix''' is a Swiss [[singer-songwriter]]. She was born in 1983, in Liege, Belgium<ref>http://www.nosenchanteurs.eu/index.php/2014/11/14/en-passant-par-la-loraine/</ref>, where her parents were working at that moment. The family moved back to Geneva soon after that.\n\n==Education==\nHer educational background is in Arts, majoring in music. She also attended different courses and workshops on music composition and lyricism in Paris with the famous songwriter Claude Lemesle.\n\n==Career==\nSince 2006, she has worked with the pianist from Lausanne, Tim Haller.\n\nOver her career she has performed in different regions in Switzerland and France, Belgium and Canada.\n\nHer first album, \"Mine de rien\" <ref>http://www.nosenchanteurs.eu/index.php/2013/05/17/chiche-loraine/</ref> was released in 2009. It had a great reception by the media and public in the French-Swiss region.\n\nHer second album \"Au coin de l\u00b4oeil\"<ref>http://artpigiste.ch/?p=1388</ref> was released in 2014.\n\nIn 2007, she was awarded the public\u00b4s choice award in the \"Voix de F\u00eate\" festival.\nIn 2009, she represented Switzerland in the Canadian Festival \u00ab Du haut des airs \u00bb\nIn 2010, she was part of the \"rencontres d'Astaffort\" created by Francis Cabrel\n\nShe was awarded the 3rd prize in the 2010 edition of the \u00ab La m\u00e9daille d'or de la chanson \u00bb<ref>http://www.meddor.ch/laureats.php</ref> in Saignel\u00e9gier, Switzerland.\n\nIn 2013, she took part in the [https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Festival_Pause_Guitare#2013 \"Pause Guitare\"]<ref>https://www.ladepeche.fr/article/2013/02/14/1560826-iggy-pop-et-mika-tetes-d-affiche-de-pause-guitare-2013.html</ref> Festival, which included artists like Mika and Iggy Pop.\n\nIn 2019, she released on youtube one of her new songs, \"Autant de Prenoms\" telling the story of the names that have marked her life in different ways <ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=420A6wmmlYw</ref>.\n\n==External links==\n* https://www.lorainefelix.ch/\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Felix, Loraine}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swiss singer-songwriters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Notability|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:Loraine Felix.jpg|thumb|Loraine Felix]]\n\n'''Loraine Felix''' is a Swiss [[singer-songwriter]]. She was born in 1983, in Liege, Belgium<ref>http://www.nosenchanteurs.eu/index.php/2014/11/14/en-passant-par-la-loraine/</ref>, where her parents were working at that moment. The family moved back to Geneva soon after that.\n\n==Education==\nHer educational background is in Arts, majoring in music. She also attended different courses and workshops on music composition and lyricism in Paris with the famous songwriter Claude Lemesle.\n\n==Career==\nSince 2006, she has worked with the pianist from Lausanne, Tim Haller.\n\nOver her career she has performed in different regions in Switzerland and France, Belgium and Canada.\n\nHer first album, \"Mine de rien\" <ref>http://www.nosenchanteurs.eu/index.php/2013/05/17/chiche-loraine/</ref> was released in 2009. It had a great reception by the media and public in the French-Swiss region.\n\nHer second album \"Au coin de l\u00b4oeil\"<ref>http://artpigiste.ch/?p=1388</ref> was released in 2014.\n\nIn 2007, she was awarded the public\u00b4s choice award in the \"Voix de F\u00eate\" festival.\nIn 2009, she represented Switzerland in the Canadian Festival \u00ab Du haut des airs \u00bb\nIn 2010, she was part of the \"rencontres d'Astaffort\" created by Francis Cabrel\n\nShe was awarded the 3rd price in the 2010 edition of the \u00ab La m\u00e9daille d'or de la chanson \u00bb<ref>http://www.meddor.ch/laureats.php</ref> in Saignel\u00e9gier, Switzerland.\n\nIn 2013, she took part in the [https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Festival_Pause_Guitare#2013 \"Pause Guitare\"]<ref>https://www.ladepeche.fr/article/2013/02/14/1560826-iggy-pop-et-mika-tetes-d-affiche-de-pause-guitare-2013.html</ref> Festival, which included artists like Mika and Iggy Pop.\n\nIn 2019, she released on youtube one of her new songs, \"Autant de Prenoms\" telling the story of the names that have marked her life in different ways <ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=420A6wmmlYw</ref>.\n\n==External links==\n* https://www.lorainefelix.ch/\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Felix, Loraine}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swiss singer-songwriters]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Typo fixing, replaced: 3rd price \u2192 3rd prize", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loraine_Felix"}
{"title_page": "1921 Auckland Rugby League season", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThe 1921 season of [[Auckland Rugby League]] was its 13th. Seventy two teams played across its six main grades.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Activities in Auckland/Review of Last Season\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LIX| issue=18050\n| date = 1921-03-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19220327.2.127.7\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref>\n\nThe first grade competition featured seven teams, [[City Rovers]], [[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]], [[Maritime (rugby league)|Maritime]], [[North Shore Albions|Devonport]], [[Grafton Athletic|Fire Brigade]] (formerly Grafton Athletic), [[Newton Rangers]], and [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]]. [[City Rovers]] comfortably won the senior championship for the 4th time with a 8 win, 1 draw, 0 loss record ahead of Maritime who were unable to repeat their title win from the previous season. [[City Rovers|City]] had previously won the title in 1910, 1911, and 1916. This was to be the first of 3 consecutive titles for them. They also won the Roope Rooster knockout competition for the 3rd time after previous wins in 1916 and 1918.\n\n== Club Name Changes and Mergers ==\nOn 13 April the Management Committee of the Auckland Rugby League met. At the meeting Grafton was granted permission to change its name to \u201cFire Brigade Club\u201d. [[North Shore Albions|Devonport United]] notified the league that the Devonport Borough Council had allocated the [[Devonport Domain]] for its use. During the season the club was named \u2018North Shore\u2019 and \u2018Devonport\u2019 interchangeably by both ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'' and the ''[[Auckland Star]]''. In 1920 the club had seen a merger between [[North Shore Albions]] and the Sunnyside club and agreed on the name [[North Shore Albions|Devonport United]] but it appears that the stronger club\u2019s name was still more favoured by those reporting on the games, and it was eventually the name adopted by the club. While the Kingsland Rovers club wrote asking for advice on what it should do regarding a ground for the club to play at.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = The Management Committee\n| work = New Zealand Herald| volume=LVIII| issue=17755\n| date = 1921-03-14 |page=7\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210414.2.103.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-22}}</ref>\n\n== Carlaw Park Open for Business ==\nHistory was made on 25 June when the first ever match was played on [[Carlaw Park]] between [[City Rovers]] and Maritime. The match was won by [[City Rovers]] 10 points to 8. Prior to the match an official opening ceremony was held. \u201cThe park was declared open by Hon. [[Arthur Myers]], MP. Mr and Mrs. Carlaw were each presented with a gold badge and certificate of life membership on the ground, and at the conclusion of the ceremony Mrs Carlaw kicked off for the first game on the new park\u201d.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =City Defeats Maritime At Carlaw Park/Exciting Contest Witnessed\n| page =8\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LII| issue=151\n| date = 1921-06-27\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19210627.2.112\n| accessdate = 2019-08-25}}</ref> [[City Rovers]] capped a remarkable season by winning the [[Thacker Shield]] from [[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]] on the final day of the season after having already won the Monteith Shield by winning the First Grade Championship, and the Roope Rooster Knock-out trophy.\n\n==Female Football Club Denied By the League==\nOn 12 July a meeting was held in Parnell to form a \"girls\" rugby league competition and over 40 enrolling. They were to play a game on Carlaw Park on the following Saturday afternoon. They were all aged between 16 and 20 years of age. The chairman of the Parnell club, Mr. A. R. Turner explained \"that it wished to develop the girls as well as the men, and to this end the club was being formed at the suggestion of the girls\". A trophy \"similar to the Monteith Shield\" had been donated, and \"members of the Auckland League Management Committee had donated a football, and were providing assistance in supplying jerseys. At the meeting when the time for enrollment came it was described that \"they rose in a body and fairly rushed the table, which was in danger of being overturned in the excitement of the moment\" Ivan Culpan, secretary of the league told the girls that the league would train them every evening in the lead up to the match.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Girl Footballers/League Club Formed/First Match on Saturday/Much Enthusiasm Shown\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17832\n| date = 1921-07-13\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210713.2.104\n| accessdate = 2020-02-29}}</ref> Over the next week the number of girls enrolled increased to 65. It later transpired that the members of the Auckland Rugby League who had attended had done so by invitation and were not necessarily acting on behalf of the league with the comments they had made. At the Auckland Rugby league Management meeting the following night the decision on whether to support the girls playing and affiliate the club with the league was deferred. Both G. Hunt and [[Ted Phelan|E Phelan]] spoke against allowing the girls to play.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Girl FootballClub/Question of Affiliation/League Defers Decision/Matter of Physical Welfare\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17833 \n| date = 1921-07-14\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210714.2.111\n| accessdate = 2020-02-29}}</ref> And at a meeting on 20 July the Auckland Rugby League decided to oppose the girls playing football. Mr. J. Carlaw said that medical opinion was in opposition to females playing the sport. Mr Stallworthy and Mr. E Feilding suggested a trial game with modified rules take place with doctors watching but the request was declined.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Girl Footballers\n| page =7\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]| volume=LII| issue=172 \n| date = 1921-07-21\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19210721.2.93\n| accessdate = 2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n    {{s-bef|before=[[1920 Auckland Rugby League season|1920]]}}\n    {{s-ttl|title=13th [[Auckland Rugby League]] season\n    |years=1921}}\n    {{s-aft|after=[[1922 Auckland Rugby League season|1922]]}}\n    {{end}}\n\n== First Grade Championship ==\n=== Final Standings ===\n{|\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=175 |Team\n!width=20 abbr=\"Played\" |Pld\n!width=20 abbr=\"Won\" |W\n!width=20 abbr=\"Drawn\" |D\n!width=20 abbr=\"Lost\" |L\n!width=20 abbr=\"For\" |F\n!width=20 abbr=\"Against\" |A\n!width=20 abbr=\"Points\" |Pts\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[City Rovers]]\n|9||8||1||0||250||50||'''17'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Maritime (rugby league)|Maritime]]\n|9||6||0||3||135||112||'''12'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]]\n|9||5||0||4||167||122||'''10'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]]\n|9||5||0||4||138||99||'''10'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Newton Rangers]]\n|9||3||1||5||83||129||'''7'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[North Shore Albions|Devonport United]]\n|7||1||0||6||61||132||'''2'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Grafton Athletic|Fire Brigade]]\n|8||1||0||7||49||179||'''2'''\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Monteith Shield Fixtures ===\n\n===Round 1===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 23 April\n| time = 3:00\n| home = City\n| score = 22\u20135\n| report = <ref name=\"autoRefA\">{{cite news\n| title =Opening of the Season\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17764\n| date = 1921-04-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210425.2.110.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-22}}</ref>\n| away = Marist\n| try1 = [[Alf Townsend]], [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]], [[Bert Laing]], H Hawkes\n| con1 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]] 4\n| pen1 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]]\n| try2 = [[Bill Stormont]]\n| con2 =\n| pen2 = [[Bill Stormont]] 1 mark\n| stadium = Victoria Park 1\n| attendance = 6000\n| referee = W Murray\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 23 April\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Devonport\n| score = 3\u20132\n| report = <ref name=\"autoRefA\" />\n| away = Fire Brigade\n| try1 = J Price\n| con1 =\n| pen1 =\n| try2 =\n| con2 =\n| pen2 = [[Charles Woolley (rugby league)|Charles Woolley]]\n| stadium = Victoria Park 2\n| attendance = 6000\n| referee = Clayton\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 23 April\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Newton\n| score = 13\u20133\n| report = <ref name=\"autoRefA\" />\n| away = Ponsonby\n| try1 = [[Bill Cloke]], [[Clarrie Polson]], L Newdick\n| con1 = [[Craddock Dufty]] 2\n| pen1 =\n| try2 = W Edwards\n| con2 =\n| pen2 =\n| stadium = Auckland Domain\n| attendance =\n| referee = W Ripley\n}}\n\n===Round 2===\n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 30 April\n| time = 3:00\n| home = City\n| score = 33\u20132\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =City Defeats Maritime\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| volume=LVIII| issue=17770\n| date = 1921-05-02\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19210502.2.110.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-22}}</ref>| away = Maritime\n| try1 = [[Ben Davidson (rugby league)|Ben Davidson]], [[Bert Laing]] 2, T Peckham, V Thomas 2,[[Alf Townsend]]\n| con1 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]] 5\n| pen1 = [[Bill Davidson (rugby league)|Bill Davidson]] 1 mark\n| try2 = \n| con2 =\n| pen2 = [[Eric Grey]]\n| stadium = Auckland Domain 1\n| attendance = 7500\n| referee = A Ferguson\n}}\n \n{{rugbybox collapsible\n| date = 30 April\n| time = 3:00\n| home = Newton\n| score = 16\u201310\n| report = <ref>{{cite news\n| title =Newton Too Good For North Shore\n| page =7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]| v